Demonstration of buffer allocation and overhead.


In this context, overhead means the extra cost beyond the actual message data.
For MPI buffered sends, that extra cost is the bookkeeping space the MPI
library may need to store and manage each message in the user-provided buffer.

So if your message payload is the actual data you want to send, the overhead is
the additional bytes needed so MPI can pack, track, and later deliver that
message safely. The MPI docs describe MPI_BSEND_OVERHEAD as the maximum amount
of buffer space that MPI_Bsend may use per message.

    src: https://docs.open-mpi.org/en/v5.0.1/man-openmpi/man3/MPI_Buffer_attach.3.html

pack_size is the space for the actual integers, and MPI_BSEND_OVERHEAD is the
extra space MPI may need for one buffered send. If you had two buffered sends
outstanding, you would need to add the overhead twice


MPI_Pack_size vs 4*sizeof(int)

    4*sizeof(int) is only the raw storage for four integers in memory.
    MPI_Pack_size gives the amount of space MPI says is needed to pack that
    data for sending with the chosen datatype and communicator.

    For simple contiguous built-in types like MPI_INT,

        MPI_Pack_size(4, MPI_INT, comm, &pack_size)

    is often close to

        4*sizeof(int)

    but it is still the portable choice because MPI is allowed to represent
    packed data in a way that is not identical to your in-memory layout. It
    also matters more for derived datatypes, heterogeneous systems, or anything
    that is not a plain contiguous block of bytes.


If you omit MPI_BSEND_OVERHEAD

    If you forget to include MPI_BSEND_OVERHEAD, your attached buffer may be
    too small, and MPI_Bsend can fail with a buffer-related error such as
    MPI_ERR_BUFFER. In practice, that means MPI may not be able to queue the
    message in the user buffer, even though the payload itself would fit.

    A good rule is:

        buffer_size = pack_size + MPI_BSEND_OVERHEAD;

    and if you plan to have multiple buffered sends outstanding, add that
    overhead for each one.


Practical note

    For many programs, buffered send is not the best default choice. The MPI
    docs and user discussions often recommend standard blocking sends or
    nonblocking sends instead, because buffered mode makes it easy to
    under-allocate and hard to predict how much space you really need.

        src: https://stackoverflow.com/a/44087662
